Celebrating National Mutt Day by hanging out with a few of our #mutts and drinking a few Salty Dogs. And, since these two #chickens are ALSO mutts, we ALSO did a variation called a Salty Hen (basically a Salty Dog with egg white and a bit of honey syrup added to it), because……I’m me.
-
To make it:
Shake 3 oz fresh grapefruit juice, 1.5 oz #vodka, .5 oz honey syrup (1:1 honey and hot water mixed thoroughly then cooled), 1 medium egg white, and a pinch of salt in a cocktail shaker with ice and shake until chilled and frothy. Strain into a salt-rimmed coupe.
-
If you want a Salty Dog, omit the egg and the syrup (although I always put a touch of syrup in mine) and serve on the rocks.
-
Also of note: one of these mutts is molting and is legit a Salty Hen.

#AD | This crazy chicken lady has only two requirements on a hot summer day: a nice, cool @vitafrute canned vodka soda, and some SPF (submerged poultry feet). Vita Frute is the absolute perfect summertime poolside sip—no matter what your pool looks like or…yanno…who’s in it. It’s so SO tasty straight from the can (only 100 calories each with some really gorg flavors like this here Blood Orange). But also, it’s pretty fantastic mixed up into a refreshing spritzy cocktail such as this Orange-Hibiscus Sparkling Tea. And well…maybe since you selflessly let your chickens cool their hot little chicken feet in your kiddie pool, you deserve both a can of Vita Frute AND a Sparkling Tea cocktail. Just a thought.
-
To make the Orange-Hibiscus Sparkling Tea:
-
To an ice-filled rocks glass, add:
-3 oz. brewed then cooled hibiscus tea
-0.5 oz Orange Marmalade Syrup (1:1 ratio of orange marmalade and hot water, thoroughly mixed then cooled).
-Top with Blood Orange Vita Frute vodka soda, and give it a stir.
-Garnish with a slice of blood orange or reg orange, fresh mint, and edible blooms.
